:name: XIAO nRF52840 usb+wired PMW3610 split -- central Studio over USB + wired split relay
:description: Two machines. central = real studio-rpc-usb-uart image with a WIRED
:description: split link (Studio rides emulated USB CDC, console on uart0, split on
:description: uart1); peripheral = wired-split half carrying a simulated PMW3610 on
:description: SPIM0. The harness preloads the central NVS, calls `start`, then
:description: attaches the USB CDC bridge.

# Module-local variant of zmk-west-commands' platforms/usb_wired_split.resc: the
# PERIPHERAL machine here loads xiao_pmw3610.repl (SPIM0 + simulated PMW3610 +
# the LATCH-aware GPIO for the level-triggered motion IRQ) instead of the plain
# wired-split repl, so the peripheral's ZMK driver inits for real and answers
# relayed GetInfo/ReadRegister requests over the wired split event relay. The
# central is the unchanged real studio-rpc-usb-uart image on the NRF_USBD_Full
# USB platform, so it answers Studio RPC over the emulated USB CDC (attached by
# the harness after boot) -- the transport that round-trips the large relayed
# PMW3610 response, unlike the Renode Studio-UART TX path or the emulated BLE link.
#
# This script only wires everything up; the harness (pmw3610_usb_wired_split_lib.boot)
# preloads the central's NVS storage partition (erased 0xFF), issues `start` after
# connecting the console sockets, then attaches the USB CDC bridge -- so no early
# boot-banner bytes are lost.

using sysbus

# $central_platform is the real USB repl with absolute model-.py paths,
# materialized by the boot helper. PMW3610.cs / the LATCH GPIO are compiled here
# before the peripheral platform (which instantiates SPI.PMW3610) loads.
$central_bin?=@central.elf
$peripheral_bin?=@peripheral.elf
$central_platform?=@platforms/xiao_nrf52840_usb.repl
$central_console_port?=3477
$peripheral_console_port?=3478

# Both halves are xiao_ble//zmk images linked at the Adafruit-UF2 bootloader
# partition (CONFIG_FLASH_LOAD_OFFSET). LoadELF sets the entry PC, but `start`
# resets the core via VTOR, and the vector table (including every UART/GPIO IRQ
# vector) lives at the load offset, not 0. Without pointing VectorTableOffset
# there after each LoadELF, interrupts vector into empty flash -- the CPUs still
# reach main() but the split UARTE RX ISR never fires, so the peripheral
# receives no relayed command (see zmk-west-commands' usb_wired_split.resc, which
# does the same).
$vtor?=0x27000

include @platforms/PMW3610.cs
include @platforms/NRF52840_GPIO_WithLatch.cs

emulation CreateUARTHub "split_link"

# ---- central (real studio-rpc-usb-uart image + wired split on uart1) ---------
mach create "central"
machine LoadPlatformDescription $central_platform
emulation CreateServerSocketTerminal $central_console_port "central_console_term" false
connector Connect sysbus.uart0 central_console_term
connector Connect sysbus.uart1 split_link
sysbus LoadELF $central_bin
sysbus.cpu VectorTableOffset $vtor

# ---- peripheral (simulated PMW3610 on SPIM0 + wired split on uart1) ----------
mach create "peripheral"
machine LoadPlatformDescription @platforms/xiao_pmw3610.repl
emulation CreateServerSocketTerminal $peripheral_console_port "peripheral_console_term" false
connector Connect sysbus.uart0 peripheral_console_term
connector Connect sysbus.uart1 split_link
sysbus LoadELF $peripheral_bin
sysbus.cpu VectorTableOffset $vtor
